# Learning Objectives

::: lob
1.  Identify cases when it is appropriate to use risk difference, relative risk, or odds ratios
:::

2.  Expand work on contingency tables to evaluate the agreement or reproducibility using Cohen’s Kappa

## Approximate OR and RR

-   Notice that odds ratio is **not equivalent** to relative risk (or risk ratio)

 

-   However, when the **probability of "success" is small** (e.g., rare disease), $\widehat{OR}$ is a nice approximation of $\widehat{RR}$ $$\widehat{OR}=\frac{{\widehat{p}}_1/(1-{\widehat{p}}_1)}{{\widehat{p}}_2/(1-{\widehat{p}}_2)}=\widehat{RR}\cdot \frac{1-\widehat{p_2}}{1-\widehat{p_1}}$$

    -   The fraction $\frac{1-\widehat{p_2}}{1-\widehat{p_1}} \approx 1$ **IF BOTH** $\widehat{p}_1 < 0.1$ and $\widehat{p}_2 < 0.1$

 

-   The $\widehat{OR}$ and $\widehat{RR}$ are not very close to each other in SHS: diabetes not a rare disease

    -   $\widehat{OR} = 4.65$
    -   $\widehat{RR} = 3.29$

## Example where OR does approximate RR

-   An example where a disease rare over the whole sample (\~1%), AND $\widehat{p}_1 < 0.1$ and $\widehat{p}_2 < 0.1$

![](./images/rare_dis2.png){fig-align="center"}

$$\widehat{RR}=\frac{0.0826}{0.00102}=81.083$$ 
$$\widehat{OR} = \frac{0.0826(1-0.0826)}{0.00102(1-0.00102)}=88.29$$
$$\widehat{RR} \approx \widehat{OR}$$

## Example where OR does not approximate RR

-   An example where a disease rare over the whole sample (\~1%), but $\widehat{p}_1 > 0.1$ and $\widehat{p}_2 < 0.1$

    -   $\widehat{OR}$ is not a good estimate of $\widehat{RR}$ in “rare” disease

![](./images/rare_dis.png){fig-align="center"}

-   $\widehat{p}_1$ is 0.5: thus $\widehat{OR}$ and $\widehat{RR}$ are very different

$$\widehat{RR}=\frac{0.5}{0.00102}=490 \text{ and } \widehat{OR} = \frac{0.5(1-0.5)}{0.00102(1-0.00102)}=981$$

## Poll Everywhere Question 2

## RR in retrospective case-control study (1/3)

-   In retrospective case-control studies: we **identify cases** (patients with the outcome), then select a number of controls (patients without the outcome)

    -   Case-control study to require **much smaller sample size** than equivalent cohort studies

    -   So we pick out the cases and controls first, **then see if there is exposure**

 

-   However, the [proportion of cases in the sample]{style="color:#5B9BD5; font-weight: bold;"} **does not** represent the [proportion of cases in the population]{style="color:#70AD47; font-weight: bold;"}

    -   RR compares probability of the outcome (case) for exposed and unexposed groups
    -   Number of outcomes has been artificially inflated for case-control study

## RR in retrospective case-control study (2/3)

-   Assume a [1:2 case-control study sample]{style="color:#5B9BD5; font-weight: bold;"} summarized in below table:

 

:::::: columns
::: {.column width="15%"}
:::

::: {.column width="70%"}
![](./images/retro_RR_tab1.png){fig-align="center"}
:::

::: {.column width="15%"}
:::
::::::

-   Assume we compute the RR as if it is from a cohort study:

$$\widehat{RR}=\frac{\widehat{p_1}}{\widehat{p_2}}=\frac{n_{11}/n_{1}}{n_{21}/n_{2}}=\frac{40/80}{60/220}=1.8333$$

## RR in cohort study (prospective or retrospective)

-   In real world, the proportion of controls (not diseased) is typically much higher. Assume the table below shows the [**proportion in the population in a cohort study**]{style="color:#70AD47; font-weight: bold;"}:

:::::: columns
::: {.column width="15%"}
:::

::: {.column width="70%"}
![](./images/retro_RR_tab2.png){fig-align="center"}
:::

::: {.column width="15%"}
:::
::::::

-   The estimated RR for the patient population is:

$$\widehat{RR}=\frac{\widehat{p_1}}{\widehat{p_2}}=\frac{n_{11}/n_{1}}{n_{21}/n_{2}}=\frac{400/4400}{600/16600}=2.5152$$

## Notes for Odds Ratios

::: columns
::: column
-   It can be interpreted either as...

    -   Odds of **event** for group 1 vs. group 2 individuals
        - We've called these $\widehat{\text{odds}}_1$ and $\widehat{\text{odds}}_2$
    -   Odds of **group 1** for individuals with (success) vs. without (failure) the event of interest
        - We can call this $\widehat{\text{odds}}_{S}$ and $\widehat{\text{odds}}_{F}$
:::
::: column
![](./images/ct.png){fig-align="center"}
:::
:::

$$\widehat{OR}_{1v2}=\dfrac{\widehat{\text{odds}}_1}{\widehat{\text{odds}}_2}=\dfrac{{\widehat{p}}_1/(1-{\widehat{p}}_1)}{{\widehat{p}}_2/(1-{\widehat{p}}_2)} = \dfrac{\dfrac{n_{11}}{n_1} / \dfrac{n_{10}}{n_1}}{\dfrac{n_{21}}{n_2} / \dfrac{n_{20}}{n_2}} = \dfrac{\dfrac{n_{11}}{n_{10}}}{\dfrac{n_{21}}{n_{20}}} = \dfrac{\dfrac{n_{11}}{n_{21}}}{\dfrac{n_{10}}{n_{20}}} = \dfrac{\dfrac{n_{11}}{n_S} / \dfrac{n_{21}}{n_S}}{\dfrac{n_{10}}{n_F} / \dfrac{n_{20}}{n_F}}=\dfrac{{\widehat{p}}_S/(1-{\widehat{p}}_S)}{{\widehat{p}}_F/(1-{\widehat{p}}_F)} = \dfrac{\widehat{\text{odds}}_S}{\widehat{\text{odds}}_F}$$

## OR in retrospective case-control study

-   While we cannot estimate RR from a case-control study, we can still estimate OR for case-control study

    -   OR does not require us to distinguish between the outcome variable and explanatory variable in the contingency table

        -   AKA: Odds ratio of disease comparing exposed to not exposed is same as odds ratio of being exposed comparing diseased and not diseased

 

::::: columns
::: column
-   For case-control study where the probability of having outcome is small, the $\widehat{OR}$ is a nice approximation to $\widehat{RR}$

